Hi folks. <br>
I'm just popping in to relate to you the latest message from the dev team. This is from one of our designers: <br>
<br>
--- <br>
<br>
We've ran through the Evade mechanics I described yesterday, and made a few refinements. <br>
<br>
If Evading while at the top of the hate list, you will still be moved between the current #2 and #3 person on the hate list. In addition, if the amount of hate reduction calculated is less than 500 actual points, it becomes 500. <br>
<br>
This insures that Evade will always be at least as effective as Jolt, and it will mitigate the Multiple Rogue Syndrome many of you fear. Example: <br>
<br>
Rogue1 has 10000 hate <br>
Warrior2 has 9800 hate <br>
Ranger3 has 9795 hate. <br>
<br>
Using the formula (#2hate-#3hate)/2(+#3hate)=Rogue Evade hate, the Rogue1 would be set to #2 with 9798 hate. 2 points lower than the new #1 player, and 202 points lower than his initial hate. Sucks, doesn't it? <br>
<br>
Since 202 is less than 500, the actual hate would be adjusted 500 points lower, setting Rogue1 to 9500 hate, which could actually move him lower than #3. Doesn't suck. <br>
<br>
Now if the three players at the top of the list were all rogues, the rotation of the three would not be as likely, since each one of them drops by a minimum of 500 points, IF there are other non-rogue damage dealers around. The non-rogues are much more likely to claim top spot rather than the trio of rogues. Lets throw some more math out here for you: <br>
<br>
Above example, Rogue1 just evaded, setting his hate to 9500. <br>
<br>
Warrior2 is actually Rogue2, with 9800 points of hate, now the top spot. He evades, placing him between 9795 and 9500, which is 9648. 9800-9648 is only 152, so he is bumped down 500 to 9300. <br>
<br>
Ranger3 is actually Rogue3. He is now in the top spot with 9795. He evades, placed between 9500 and 9300, to 9400. Again, less than 500, so he is moved to 9295. <br>
<br>
Now, you say that Rogue1 at 9500 should be back on top of the hate list, right? This could be the case, but you have to <br>
<br>
realize that while these three Evades were going on, there may well have been other damage dealers in the encounter who have exceeded 9500 hate. <br>
<br>
Each time a string of rogues evades, it becomes more and more efficient for the evader, pushing them down to the point where they are eclipsed by the other damage dealers. <br>
<br>
We're testing this out now, and so far it looks pretty good. <br>
<br>
In addition, if Evading while not #1 (pre-Evade), your total hate is reduced by 10% OR 500, whichever is greater, not to go below 128. <br>
<br>
We've also looked a few more rogue issues, and expect to have them adjusted in the following weeks. None of these are promised, keep this in mind, but we are looking into them. <br>
<br>
Reduction of Min Range for throwing weapons. Not a removal, but a reduction, to around 3-5 feet. Should make them easier to use. <br>
<br>
Instill Doubt still on the same timer as it is currently, but allowing that first backstab or special attack to land after ID goes off. This will happen. Still rewards those of you with good timing. <br>
<br>
Apply Poison putting the Rogue in kneel mode similar to bind wounds, and releasing him when complete. Great player idea, this will probably happen. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
